Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by (Acheampong Andrews)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 174952 entries in the dataset with 18 columns (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_date, end_date, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip ).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out how long does the average trip takes.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that duration_sec will have the strongest effect on each bike_id: the smallest the duration_sec, the faster the bike_id. I will also look into the gender column, to see the average fasters gender in the dataset.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section I will start looking at the distribution of the variables of interest.

Duration second has a long-tailed distribution, with a lot of small time end, and few on the greatest time end. When plotted on a log-scale, the duration seconds distribution looks a normal distribution, with the peak between 20000 and 60000, and its slightly skewed to the right.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration_sec variable took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked normal distribution, with a peak between $20000 and $60000, and it is slightly skewed to the right.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike_id variables, a number of outlier points were identified. Overall, these points can be characterized by an inconsistency between the recorded value of depth, and the value that would be derived from using start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike_id. For safety, all of these points were removed from the dataset to move forwards.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color=default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_bike_samp, y_vars = ['duration_sec', 'bike_id'], x_vars = categoric_vars,
                height = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid)
plt.show();

<Figure size 1000x1000 with 0 Axes>

In [27]:
def cuberoot_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing cube root and cube operations """
    if not inverse:
        return x ** (1/3)
    else:
        return x ** 3
In [28]:
# compute the logarithm of duration_sec to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df_bike['lod_duration_sec'] = df_bike['duration_sec'].apply(log_trans)
df_bike['cr_bike_id'] = df_bike['bike_id'].apply(cuberoot_trans)
